english:
  title: Blue Words for the Great One Ritual of Rain Prayer
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    FIRST OFFERING

    Heaven sees and hears through the people, and fulfills their desires. When the moon reaches the star Bi, the rains come in torrents—swift and certain in their response. Through this purification ritual, I humbly seek to be drenched in true grace.

    SECOND OFFERING

    The Way attains the One and becomes supreme, silently orchestrating the transformations of creation. When ritual is performed twice, reverence deepens. With utmost sincerity of heart, I now devoutly attend, hoping to receive abundant rain.

    THIRD OFFERING

    Heaven shows no favoritism, yet sustains the virtuous. Ever watchful and luminous, it oversees all. When people err, calamities arise from such discord. How can I not tremble and reform? With bowed head, I offer my deepest sincerity; with upturned face, I seek the mysteries of heaven.

    Reflecting upon myself—though unworthy, I have inherited this great mandate. Governance requires virtue; I know I should be watchful day and night, vigilant and diligent. Yet my duties are burdensome; can I truly avoid excess in reward and punishment? Such discord summons inauspicious signs that pile upon one another.

    Drought has brought calamity. Spring passed without rain; summer's drought grew worse. Insects devoured the crops—seedlings and leaves alike consumed, leaving only sickness in their wake. I grieve for my ancestors' downfall and have performed rites to every god, yet no manifest blessing appears. Clouds gather only to disperse; the sun shines forth once more. On the very month for weeding, hail descended, damaging the fields. And when the rainy season came, snow fell—startling all who heard of it. Not only have the grains withered, but even grass and trees have burned to ash.

    Though such suffering springs from human error, I fear the heavenly heart may grow weary of sustaining life. I, in my inadequate virtue, deserve punishment, yet how can I bear to watch the innocent starve? Each time I contemplate this, tears fall. Would that the suffering came to me alone!

    The Lord's judgment rests in heaven's wisdom, yet it is fitting to petition for the people's sake. I send my servants to the altar, humbly presenting this ritual. May sincere devotion reach the luminous gaze above, dispelling all malevolent influences. Let blessed rain fall upon all, so that the four seasons proceed in order and all things flourish. Let heaven's way flow true and undeviating. Let the six resources be cultivated and the three great matters be governed, so that the people's livelihood grows ever richer and more abundant. May we gather blessings from the Nine Chapters of the sage king, and may our dynasty endure beyond the ancient powers. This I humbly pray.
  footnotes:
    - The 'star Bi' (畢) is one of the 28 lunar mansions in traditional Chinese astronomy, associated with rainfall.
    - This is a formal petition ritual (醮禮青詞文) performed at the Daoist altar, structured in three ritual offerings (初獻, 二獻, 三獻).
    - The 'Six Resources' (六府) and 'Three Great Matters' (三事) refer to Confucian principles of governance and the well-being of the people.
    - The reference to the 'Nine Chapters' (洪範九疇) alludes to the sage king Qiji's teachings on proper governance.
    - The 'ancient powers' references the Nine Tripods (九鼎), symbolic of dynastic legitimacy and longevity in Chinese tradition.
